    <item>
      <title>NFL Films President Steve Sabol Dies </title>
      <description>Half of the father-son team that revolutionized sports broadcasting, the NFL Films president died Tuesday of brain cancer at age 69 in Moorestown, N.J. He leaves behind a league bigger than ever, its fans enthralled by the plot twists and characters he so deftly chronicled.</description>
      <pubDate>Tue, 18 Sep 2012 17:41:00 -0400</pubDate>
      <link>http://www.npr.org/2012/09/18/161372867/nfl-films-president-steve-sabol-dies?ft=1&amp;f=1003</link>
      <guid>http://www.npr.org/2012/09/18/161372867/nfl-films-president-steve-sabol-dies?ft=1&amp;f=1003</guid>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Half of the father-son team that revolutionized sports broadcasting, the NFL Films president died Tuesday of brain cancer at age 69 in Moorestown, N.J. He leaves behind a league bigger than ever, its fans enthralled by the plot twists and characters he so deftly chronicled.</p><p><a href="http://www.npr.org/templates/email/emailAFriend.php?storyId=161372867">&raquo; E-Mail This</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://del.icio.us/post?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.npr.org%2Ftemplates%2Fstory%2Fstory.php%3FstoryId%3D161372867">&raquo; Add to Del.icio.us</a></p>]]></content:encoded>
